<font color="#FF0000">CONFLICT AVOIDANCE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov  3 20:06:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Beth,<br><br>
The real answer is to avoid conflict.  I have noticed when I am in a specific mood I am so intensely involved I don't want to be bothered.  It usually results in some sort of insensitive comment from me.  If my wife tries to force her opinion it results in me avoiding conversation.  I just walk away to avoid the situation.  If it persists it can be a yelling contest.  Don't agree with everything, be yourself.  That is a privilege my wife maintains. <br><br>
If you don't understand what is happening you might assume he doesn't value your opinion.  We learn conflict avoidance, withdrawal, silence, a thousand mile stare.  We do value opinion just not at certain times.<br><br>
Always wait for the calmer times to talk about the distorted periods.  It is almost impossible to insert yourself into his mind or reality concept at that moment.  He knows you are there and he will return.  My wife would say maintain yourself.  Giving is not a one way street.<br><br>
Don't be afraid to ignore him until he comes to you.  We can be easily spoiled.  I know.<br><br>
Stay in touch and good luck
<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


